TY  - JOUR
AB  - We investigate the value of active mutual fund
                                                management by examining the stockholdings and trades
                                                of mutual funds. We fine that stocks widely held by
                                                funds do not outperform other stocks. However,
                                                stocks purchased by funds have significantly higher
                                                returns than stocks they sell—this is true for large
                                                stocks as well as small stocks, and for value stocks
                                                as well as growth stocks. We find that
                                                growth-oriented funds exhibit better stock selection
                                                skills than income-oriented funds. Finally, we find
                                                only weak evidence that funds with the best past
                                                performance have better stock-picking skills than
                                                funds with the worst past performance.
